        -:    1:/**
        -:    2: * cjit.c – Non-blocking JIT compiler engine.
        -:    3: *
        -:    4: * ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
        -:    5: * │                       Architecture Overview                             │
        -:    6: * ├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
        -:    7: * │                                                                         │
        -:    8: * │   Runtime threads (any number)                                          │
        -:    9: * │   ────────────────────────────                                          │
        -:   10: * │   Hot path per call (CJIT_DISPATCH / cjit_get_func_counted):            │
        -:   11: * │     fn = atomic_load(&table[id].func_ptr);  ← single acquire-load      │
        -:   12: * │     fn(args…);                              ← indirect call             │
        -:   13: * │     tls_counts[id]++;                       ← thread-local byte incr   │
        -:   14: * │     if (tls_counts[id] >= THRESHOLD)        ← flush every N calls      │
        -:   15: * │         atomic_fetch_add(&call_cnt, N);     ← amortised atomic flush   │
        -:   16: * │                                                                         │
        -:   17: * │   Per-thread TLS batch counting                                         │
        -:   18: * │   ──────────────────────────────                                        │
        -:   19: * │   Each calling thread owns a private uint8_t tls_counts[MAX_FUNCTIONS] │
        -:   20: * │   array (~1 KB TLS per thread).  The hot path only writes to this       │
        -:   21: * │   thread-private array; no shared-memory traffic until the batch fills. │
        -:   22: * │   func_ptr (cache line 0) and call_cnt (cache line 1) are on separate   │
        -:   23: * │   cache lines: func_ptr stays in "Shared" state on all cores for the    │
        -:   24: * │   lifetime of steady-state execution.                                   │
        -:   25: * │                                                                         │
        -:   26: * │   Background threads (started by cjit_start)                           │
        -:   27: * │   ─────────────────────────────────────────                             │
        -:   28: * │                                                                         │
        -:   29: * │   ┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐  │
        -:   30: * │   │  Monitor thread (×1)                                         │  │
        -:   31: * │   │   • Wakes every monitor_interval_ms (nanosleep, low CPU)     │  │
        -:   32: * │   │   • Maintains per-function EMA of call rate                  │  │
        -:   33: * │   │   • 5-gate data-driven promotion (all must pass):            │  │
        -:   34: * │   │     1. Hard recompile cap  (max_recompiles_per_func)         │  │
        -:   35: * │   │     2. Scaled rate thresh  (+scale_pct% per recompile)       │  │
        -:   36: * │   │     3. Stability streak    (hot_confirm_cycles + rc×extra)   │  │
        -:   37: * │   │     4. O3 uptime gate      (min_uptime_for_tier2_ms)         │  │
        -:   38: * │   │     5. Scaled O3 min-calls (min_calls_for_tier2 × (1+rc))   │  │
        -:   39: * │   │   • Adaptive cooloff: max(cfg.cooloff, 2×last_compile_ms)    │  │
        -:   40: * │   │   • Non-blocking async IR prefetch via ir_cache_prefetch()   │  │
        -:   41: * │   └─────────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────┘  │
        -:   42: * │                                 │  (per-thread lock-free MPMC queues)│
        -:   43: * │   ┌─────────────────────────────▼────────────────────────────────┐  │
        -:   44: * │   │  Compiler threads (×[1..CJIT_COMPILER_THREADS], dynamic)     │  │
        -:   45: * │   │   • Each owns one MPMC queue; tasks routed by func_id%%n      │  │
        -:   46: * │   │   • Work-steals from neighbours when own queue empty         │  │
        -:   47: * │   │   • Blocks on shared condvar (instant wake on enqueue)       │  │
        -:   48: * │   │   • Fetches IR via ir_cache_get_ir() (COLD→WARM on miss)     │  │
        -:   49: * │   │   • Compiles via posix_spawnp(cc) — no shell overhead        │  │
        -:   50: * │   │   • Atomic func_table_swap + dgc_retire(old_handle)          │  │
        -:   51: * │   │   • Writes last_compile_duration_ms for adaptive cooloff      │  │
        -:   52: * │   └─────────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────┘  │
        -:   53: * │                                 │  (lock-free retire stack)          │
        -:   54: * │   ┌─────────────────────────────▼────────────────────────────────┐  │
        -:   55: * │   │  GC thread (×1, inside deferred_gc)                          │  │
        -:   56: * │   │   • Pre-allocated pool of retire_entry_t nodes (no malloc)   │  │
        -:   57: * │   │   • Sleeps exactly until next handle becomes freeable        │  │
        -:   58: * │   │   • Exponential back-off when retire stack is empty          │  │
        -:   59: * │   │   • dlclose handles older than grace_period_ms               │  │
        -:   60: * │   └──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘  │
        -:   61: * │                                                                       │
        -:   62: * │   IR cache (per engine, background threads)                           │
        -:   63: * │   ──────────────────────────────────────                              │
        -:   64: * │   ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐    │
        -:   65: * │   │  I/O prefetch pool (×[0..cfg.io_threads])                   │    │
        -:   66: * │   │   • Drains pf_buf FIFO of prefetch requests                 │    │
        -:   67: * │   │   • Promotes COLD IR → WARM in background (hides disk I/O)  │    │
        -:   68: * │   └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘    │
        -:   69: * │   ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐    │
        -:   70: * │   │  Memory-pressure monitor thread (×1)                        │    │
        -:   71: * │   │   • Polls /proc/meminfo; adjusts HOT/WARM cache capacities  │    │
        -:   72: * │   │   • Proactively evicts HOT→WARM / WARM→COLD under pressure  │    │
        -:   73: * │   └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘    │
        -:   74: * │                                                                         │
        -:   75: * └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
        -:   76: *
        -:   77: * Thread safety
        -:   78: * ─────────────
        -:   79: * func_ptr  : Written with memory_order_release (compiler thread only).
        -:   80: *             Read  with memory_order_acquire   (runtime + monitor threads).
        -:   81: *
        -:   82: * call_cnt  : Incremented with memory_order_relaxed (runtime threads).
        -:   83: *             Read    with memory_order_relaxed (monitor thread).
        -:   84: *             Relaxed ordering is correct here because we only care about
        -:   85: *             the approximate magnitude, not strict ordering with any
        -:   86: *             other shared variable.
        -:   87: *
        -:   88: * compile_lock per entry: Held by a compiler thread during the entire
        -:   89: *             compilation pass.  Prevents two compiler threads from
        -:   90: *             simultaneously recompiling the same function.  This mutex
        -:   91: *             is NEVER held on the runtime call path.
        -:   92: *
        -:   93: * in_queue   : Atomic bool set by monitor/request before enqueue, cleared
        -:   94: *             by compiler thread after dequeue (but before compilation so
        -:   95: *             that a new enqueue can happen if needed while this compile
        -:   96: *             is in flight).
        -:   97: *
        -:   98: * Global stats counters: updated with relaxed atomics; no ordering required.
        -:   99: *
        -:  100: * RCU-style atomic swap
        -:  101: * ─────────────────────
        -:  102: *   1. Compiler thread compiles new code → new_fn, new_handle.
        -:  103: *   2. Acquires entry->compile_lock.
        -:  104: *   3. old_handle = entry->dl_handle.
        -:  105: *   4. entry->dl_handle = new_handle.
        -:  106: *   5. atomic_store(&entry->func_ptr, new_fn, release).
        -:  107: *      ↑ This is the "pointer publish" – all subsequent acquire-loads by
        -:  108: *        runtime threads will see new_fn.  Any runtime thread that already
        -:  109: *        loaded old_fn before this store will finish its call using old code
        -:  110: *        (which is still mapped, since dlclose is deferred).
        -:  111: *   6. Releases compile_lock.
        -:  112: *   7. dgc_retire(dgc, old_handle).
        -:  113: *      ↑ After grace_period_ms, the GC thread calls dlclose(old_handle).
        -:  114: *        By that time all calls using old code have completed.
        -:  115: *
        -:  116: * Incremental recompilation
        -:  117: * ─────────────────────────
        -:  118: * The same IR source can be recompiled multiple times at increasing
        -:  119: * optimisation tiers.  The monitor thread escalates:
        -:  120: *   call_cnt ≥ hot_threshold_t1  → enqueue at OPT_O2
        -:  121: *   call_cnt ≥ hot_threshold_t2  → enqueue at OPT_O3
        -:  122: *
        -:  123: * A version counter per entry is incremented on each swap.  Stale compile
        -:  124: * tasks (whose version_req < current version) are discarded so that the
        -:  125: * compiler threads do not perform redundant work.
        -:  126: */
